%N A390582 a(n) = (2*n - sigma(n))/gcd(n, sigma(n)).
%C A390582 Empirical observation: mumbers in this sequence that are positive and close to 1 are more likely to produce regular amicable pairs under the Wiethaus's Rule (see Garcia et al).
%C A390582 The positions of -1's in the sequence are given by A153501.
%C A390582 The positions of 0's in the sequence are given by A000396.
%C A390582 The positions of 1's in the sequence are given by A271816.
%C A390582 If a(n) is negative, n is abundant (A005101).
%C A390582 If a(n) is positive, n is deficient (A005100).
%C A390582 If instead a(n) is 0, n is perfect (A000396).
%H A390582 Hayden Chesnut, <a href="/A390582/b390582.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A390582 M. Garc√≠a, J.M. Pedersen and H.J.J. te Riele, <a href="https://ir.cwi.nl/pub/10756/">Amicable pairs : a survey</a>, Fields Institute Communications, 41 (2004), 1-19. See p. 193.
%F A390582 a(n) = A033879(n)/A009194(n).
%F A390582 a(prime(n)) = prime(n) - 1, and those are also the records. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 13 2025
%e A390582 For n = 1, (2*n - sigma(n)) = 1 and gcd(n,sigma(n)) = 1 so (2*n - sigma(n))/gcd(n, sigma(n)) = 1.
%e A390582 For n = 9, a(prime(9)) = 22 = prime(9) - 1;
%p A390582 a := proc(n) NumberTheory:-SumOfDivisors(n); (2*n - %)/igcd(n, %) end: seq(a(n), n = 1..72);  # _Peter Luschny_, Nov 11 2025
%t A390582 a[n_] := (2*n - #)/GCD[n, #]& @ DivisorSigma[1, n]; Array[a, 100] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Nov 11 2025 *)
%o A390582 (Python)
